article.headline: Marbury continues unselfish play

images.name: Voskuhl Jake 031122 275x200
images.caption: Sun Jake Voskuhl left the game to get five stitches in his chin. He later returned.

article.linkText: Stoudemire's 24 points help Suns beat the Heat
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Amare Stoudemire is playing as if he's a seasoned veteran, and he has the Phoenix Suns heading in the right direction. Stoudemire, last season's Rookie of the Year, scored 24 points and Joe Johnson hit three key 3-pointers to help the Suns win their third straight game, 100-98 over the road-weary Miami Heat on Saturday night. It was the first time this season the Suns scored 100 points after setting a franchise record by going their first 11 games without reaching triple-digits in points. "It appeared like Amare's been in the league for six, seven or eight years," Phoenix coach Frank Johnson said after his first victory in four tries against the Heat since he became coach Feb. 17, 2002. "Everything about him was so calm." Stoudemire made his first six shots and finished 8-for-10 from the field. He also had a team-high eight rebounds. Point guard Stephon Marbury made sure he found Stoudemire whenever he could. "I started off hot," Stoudemire said. "Steph saw that and he rode the horse." The victory evened the Suns' record to 6-6, the third time they've reached .500 this season, but they have yet to surpass it. Johnson had 17 points, Shawn Marion 14, Scott Williams 12, Marbury 11 and Jake Voskuhl 10 for Phoenix. Rookie Dwyane Wade had a season-high 27, Lamar Odom had 24, including 17 in the second half, and Eddie Jones 22 for the Heat, who fell to 3-11 in ending their five-game West Coast trip. They are 1-9 overall on the road. After trailing 30-19 during the first period, the Suns rallied and outscored the Heat 26-14 in the second quarter for a 55-50 halftime lead. Johnson led the comeback with seven points in the period, including a 3-pointer that gave the Suns a 48-45 lead. Stoudemire topped the Suns' first-half offense with 15 points and six rebounds, while Marbury, Phoenix's leading scorer this season, continued his unselfish play of late, contributing eight assists. During the Suns' winning streak, Marbury has sacrificed his scoring and looked to pass more to his teammates. "It seems like teams are collapsing on me," he said. "That leaves people open. Amare, Shawn and others are going to be on the receiving end of some easy buckets when this happens. They're open and I'm just looking to find them." Miami, led by Jones' 11 points and Wade's 10, hit 58 percent -- 11-of-19 -- of its shots in establishing a 36-29 first-quarter lead, the Heat's highest single period of the season. But the Heat went cold in the second, shooting only 4-of-21. The Heat tied it twice late in the third period, before another 3-pointer by Johnson in the final minute gave the Suns a 76-73 lead at the end of the quarter. Miami, with the help of seven straight points by Jones, led twice early in the fourth period, before Johnson's third 3-pointer gave the Suns the lead for good at 83-82. Miami still was within one point at 98-97 after a basket by Odom, but Marbury's two free throws with 18.4 seconds left gave Phoenix its winning margin. Heat coach Stan Van Gundy took the defeat hard. "We come away with a very difficult loss," he said. "We're not a real experienced team." After Marbury's foul shots, the Heat had a chance to tie, but Odom missed a long jumper. "I thought it was going to go," Odom said.

Game notes
This was the Suns' fourth straight home game, and after playing at Denver on Tuesday night, they'll return to America West Arena for four more games -- against Dallas, Golden State, Indiana and Minnesota. ... This is the most lopsided series for the Suns, with Phoenix leading Miami 24-7, including 13-3 at home. ... The Heat's Loren Woods bruised his lower back on the first possession of the second quarter when he fell battling for a rebound. He didn't return. ... Phoenix did not escape without injury either when Voskuhl was smashed in the face while trying to stop Jones on a driving shot. Voskuhl needed five stitches to close the cut on his chin, then returned.
